No Express error-handling middleware. Uncaught errors will leak stack traces to clients in development and crash workers in production.

### 2. No security headers
Missing `helmet` (or equivalent) for HSTS, CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.

### 3. No rate limiting
Both endpoints are unthrottled — trivially DoS-able and vulnerable to enumeration/scraping.

### 4. No request body parsing limits
If body parsing is added later (`express.json()`), it needs a `limit` option to prevent memory-exhaustion attacks.

### 5. Unvalidated query/route params (future-proofing)
Endpoints currently take no input, but `/users` likely needs pagination/filtering. Any future `:id` param must be validated before use.

### 6. Server lifecycle issues
- No graceful shutdown (`SIGTERM`/`SIGINT` handlers).
- `process.on('uncaughtException')` / `unhandledRejection` not handled.
